						<div id="siteNotice"><!-- CentralNotice --></div>
						<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en"><span dir="auto">List of science fiction authors</span></h1>
						<div id="bodyContent">
								<div id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
								<div id="contentSub"></div>
												<div id="jump-to-nav" class="mw-jump">
					Jump to:					<a href="#mw-navigation">navigation</a>, 					<a href="#p-search">search</a>
				</div>
				<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><p>Note that this partial list contains some authors whose works of <a href="/wiki/Fantasy_fiction" title="Fantasy fiction" class="mw-redirect">fantastic fiction</a> would today be called science fiction, even if they predate, or did not work in that genre. There is also a considerable overlap with the <a href="/wiki/List_of_fantasy_authors" title="List of fantasy authors">List of fantasy authors</a>, since many authors are equally comfortable with both genres, and in any case some works deliberately combine the two or blur the distinction. Most science fiction authors write as <a href="/wiki/Novelist" title="Novelist">novelists</a> or <a href="/wiki/Short_story_writers" title="Short story writers" class="mw-redirect">short story writers</a>, though increasingly, as the genre becomes possible, they write as <a href="/wiki/Playwright" title="Playwright">playwrights</a> or <a href="/wiki/Screen_writer" title="Screen writer" class="mw-redirect">screen writers</a>.</p>
<p>Some notable <a href="/wiki/Science_fiction" title="Science fiction">science fiction</a> <a href="/wiki/Author" title="Author">authors</a> are (in alphabetical order):</p>
<div class="toc plainlinks hlist" id="toc" style="text-align: left;">
